{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_queenofspades_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280608750/1958042701/0929.xml":{"full_text":"100 PROPOSALS\nThe Scorecard\nOn Moves to\nCut Recession\nBy DAVID KOONCE\n\u25a0tar Staff WrlUt\nAs the first session of the 85th Congress closed lsst summer,\nthe Issue uppermost In the minds of the members was the civil\nrights bill destined to be the flrst such measure to pass Congress\nin this century. All other matters were shoved into the wings.\nAmong the subjects overshadowed by civil rights was the\nslate of the economy. This despite the fact that certain warn\ning signs were discernible, even to many not trained in the\nesoteric art of economic forecast\ning\nThe Congressmen went home.\nWhen they returned in January,\nthey were ready to express them\nselves at length on a danger that\nnad presented Itself in their ab\nsence from Washington\u2014the So\nviet Sputniks. But before the new\nsession was two weeks old, new\neconomic statistics turned their\nattention to another matter\u2014the\nrecession, which had also bloomed\nin full while Congress was away.\nThe figures were alarming. They\nshowed, for example, an unem\nployment rise of almost 1 million\nin two months.\nSubsequent statistics deepened\nthe concern. As a result, the flrst\n15 weeks of the second session has\ngiven more time and headlines to\ncuring the recession than to meet\ning the challenge of the Sputniks\nThis is a congressional election\nyear, and the state of the pocket\nbook is clearly of more importance\nto the voter\u2014a fact borne out in\ngrassroots surveys\u2014than the more\nremote danger of Soviet techno\nlogical advances.\nThe Score Card\nAs things stand now. almost one\nhundred steps have either been\ntaken or proposed by the admin\nistration and Congress as reces\nsion cures. Many of these meas\nures, however, affect only very\nlimited segments of the economy.\nOthers are labeled anti-recession\nary only because such a tag is be\nlieved to give legislation an added\nadvantage now.\nIt has been the congressional\naction that has taken the head\nlines. and more often than not,\ntha most widely publicized plans\nhave carried Democratic labels.\nSenate Democratic Leader Lyndon\nJohnson has had some spectacular\nsuccess in his drive to win for his\nparty the lion\u2019s share of the credit\nfor meeting the recession head-on.\nMore than once, while administra\ntion experts were drafting cures,\nSenator Johnson and his col\nleagues have beat them to the\ndraw by coming up with similar\nplans just in time to make the\nhome editions.\nThe major actions in Congress\nso far have centered around six\nplans:\nHOUSING\nIn less that! a month's time,\na Democratic-sponsored housing\nmeasure costing SI. B billion was\nreported, debated, enacted and\nsigned into law. This was perhaps\nthe most effective anti-recession\nmeasure to date in providing an\nimmediate impact. It is expected\nto create a half-million jobs this\nyear. Already its effect is being\nfelt as builders prepare for busy\nsummer months ahead.\nHIGHWAYS\nThis, another Democratic bill\nsigned into law (despite President\nEisenhower\u2019s \"serious misgiv\nings\"), authorises a $l.B billion\nIncrease in Federal highway\nspending this year. Its sponsors\nclaimed that it would provide\n88.000 jobs this year. But the bill\nactually is not so anti-recessionary\nas it might appear. The section\nof the bill that is supposed to\nmake new jobs at the earliest\ndate 18 an item calling for S4OO\nmillion worth of work that need\nnot even be contracted for be\nfore next December. Thus its\nfull impact may not be felt until\nwell into next year. And before\nthe Federal funds are put to work,\nthe States must ante up their\nshare. At the last count, there\nwas still $2 billion available to\nthe States which had not even\nbeen programmed.\nPUBLIC WORKS\nA Democratic rivers and har\nbors improvement bill costing $1.7\nbillion was vetoed by Mr. Eisen\nhower. It had been touted by\nthe Democrats as an antl-reces\nsionary measure, but Mr. Eisen\nhower, in rejecting the bill, made\na good case for his argument that\nit could have no effect on the\nrecession\u2014unless it is expected to\nlast for years.\nThe projects, he contended,\nwould take too long. Some are\nnot even in the planning stage\nand work on many of the larger\nones could not begin for many\nmonths\u2014in some cases, perhaps\ntwo or three years. 9\nThe plan. Congress' biennial\n\"pork barrel bill,\u201d was first passed\nby the Senate over a year ago,\nwhen, of course, nobody was call\ning it a cure to a recession that\nhad not even yet begun. The\nchance of overriding the veto has\nreportedly improved in recent\nlays, and if the Democratic\nleadership can marshal the two\nthirds vote required in both\nhouses, they'll give it a try. It\nwould be the flrst Eisenhower veto\noverridden.\nCOMMUNITY WORKS\nThis is a program of Federal\nloans, increased from SIOO mil\nlion to $1 billion by the Demo\ncrats, to cities and towns for\nbuilding streets, sewers, water sys\ntems, libraries, and the like. It\nhas been approved by the Senate,\n60 to 26, and is now in the House,\nwhere it is expected to pass.\nBut Mr. Eisenhower has ex\npressed a vigorous opposition to\nthe plan, pnd if it comes to him\nin its present form, is expected\nto veto it.\nJOBLESS BENEFITS\nThe House Ways and Means\nCommittee on Tuesday approved\na Democratic plan to extend for\n16 weeks unemployment compen\nsation to those among the Na-\nSoul Ml rtpsrti on Ih* human lids si\ntha rccattion on Saga A-27.\nI _l_ J_ _ i\u2014\ntion's 5 2 million unemployed who\nl have exhausted their benefits.\nOnce again, this was a case of\nthe Democrats stealing a march\non the administration. Th? bill\napproved by the committee would\nbe wholly financed by the Federal\n.Government. It would also\u2014and\nI this provision has been bitterly\nassailed by Mr. Elsenhower\u2014ex\ntend the program to 1.8 million\nworkers who are not now covered\ni by the jobless insurance plan. Mr.\nEisenhower had asked only toi a\nI 50 per cent extension in the time\nover which the payments are\ni made, paid for by Federal loans to\nthe States. Last week the Presi\ndent hinted broadly that he would\nreject the measure in its present\ni form\nFARM PRICE FREEZE\nA resolution freezing farm price\nsupport levels at last year's fig\nures was vetoed as \"ill-advised''\nby Mr. Eisenhower on March 31.\nIt was the farm-State members\net Congress in both parties who,\nas backers of the resolution,\nclaimed it would help stem the re\ni cession because it was \"designed\nto maintain farm Income and\nfarm purchasing power.\u201d An\noverturn of the veto seemed high\nly unlikely, even in the unprobable\nevent that it is attempted.\nOther congressional activity in\nthe field includes:\nApproval of two resolutions\nasking the administration to speed\nI up civil and military works pro\ngrams for which money already\nhas been voted.\nConsideration of legislation for\nmore and faster spending on air\nports.\nA proposal by Western mem\nbers to Increase outlays on recla\nmation projects.\nExecutive Moves\nThe Administrations most ef\nfective moves have been in the\nareas of;\nHOUSING\nAfter passage of the big hous\ning bill by Congress, Mr. Eisen\nhower canceled the 2 per cent\ndown payment required for GI\nhousing mortgages guaranteed by\nthe Veterans Administration. Pre\nviously. the Administration had\nlowered down payments on FHA\nhomes and had released addition\nal Government mortgage funds.\nDEFENSE SPENDING\nThe greatest potential stimulant\noriginating in the administration\nwas provided by an order increas\ning the placement of defense con\ntracts from the $7.9 billion let in\nthe last six months of 1957 by\n$5.5 billion, to $13.4 billion in the\nfirst half of 1958. It is doubtful,\nhowever, that the economy will\nfeel this shot in the arm until\nlate this year.\nCREDIT\nThree times the Federal Reserve\nBoard has acted since the reces\nsion began to make credit buying\neasier and more attractive, which\nis supposed to stimulate the pur\nchasing of everything from appli\nances to homes. The discount rate\n\u2014the rate at which member banks\nborrow from the Federal Reserve\n\u2014now stands at 1V 4 per cent. The\nBoard also, in another attempt to\nshaxe loose consumer and invest\nor money, has twice reduced the\namount which it requires its\nmember banks to keep in reserve.\nThe actions have been claimed\nby both the White House and\nSenate Minority Leader Know\nland as Republican steps to fight\nthe recession, despite the fact\nthat, during the recession, credit\ndemand has stumped. Also on\nprevious occasions when critics at\ntacked the Board for restrictions\non credit. Republicans have point\ned out that the Federal Reserve is\nby law \"independent\u201d now, and\ntherefore does not come under\nWhite House authority.\nThe Big Question\nThe big question now is \"will\ntaxes be cut?\u201d\nRank-and-file members of both\nparties have come out for a tax\nl cut, despite the fact that most re-\nI cent history has completely dis\nproved the old political axiom\nthat there are millions of votes to\nbe won by tax reduction.\nAt present, both sides are hold\ning off with a sort of \"gentleman\u2019s\nagreement\u201d not to spring a tax\ncut plan without conferring to\ngether on its\ni For the Democrats, Senator\nJohnson and the party's House\ni leaders in tax matters are moving\ncautiously lest they act too soon\nand appear even to the most ob\ntuse voter to be playing with na-\nI tional solvency for political gain.\nMr Elsenhower, who previously\nwas willing to \u201cwait and see.\u201d has\nclearly stiffened his resistance to\ntax relief. Each time he is asked\nabout it, he evidences more dls\ntaste for it than before.\nThose economists whose views\nare not colored by their political\nsympathies contend that it is lm\ni possible to say whether the money\ni provided to the taxpayer by a re-\nI ductlon would even go back into\nthe economy. Some of it, all of\nit. or none of it may be either\nspent or hoarded, they point out.\ns Nevertheless, some of the best\nI opinion around town expects that,\nall things considered the reces\nsion and politics\u2014tax reduction\nwill be difficult to avoid this year.\nEditorials\nEditorial Features\nThe Economy: Hopeful Signs\nIn President Elsenhower's 1958\neconomic report, sent to Congress\non Janusry 20. he declared that\n\"the decline in business activity\nneed not be prolonged eco\nnomic growth can be resumed\nwithout extended interruption.\u201d\nThree weeks later, the President\nforecast that March would see the\n\"beginning of the end of the\ndownturn in our economy.\" On\nFebruary 20. he again said he\nsaw no danger of a \"protracted\ndecline.\u201d Another optimistic fore\ncast came from the White House\non March 8. and then on March\n28 he announced confidently that\n\u201cwe are going through the worst\nof it right now 4\u201d\nLast Wednesday. Mr. Eisenhower\nreported evidence that the reces\nsion was \u201cflattening out.\" His\nearlier expressions of optimism\nhad been, as it turned out. pre\nmature. But there are now signs\nthat his comments at Wednesday 's\npress conference might be sub\nstantiated.\nRosier Outlook\nCertainly as last week ended the\nrate of the economic downspln\nseemed to have slowed, and there\nwere economic barometer readings\nindicating that the deceleration\nwas not just a temporary thing.\nThere were also expressions of\noptimism from business execu\ntives. who in the past months\nhave been gloomy. For example:\nMachine tool orders, indicat\ning plans for future industrial\nactivity, were up 28 per cent in\nMarch over February, and were\nat the highest level since the\nrecession began last August.\nFarm Income in 1958's flrst\nquarter rose sharply, topping the\nsame 1957 period by $1.3 billion.\n(When farmers' incomes improve,\nthey buy the items -industry\nmakes.)\nGI home-building plans are\nclimbing steeply since Mr. Ei\nsenhbwer removed down pay\nment requirements.\nThe rate of new incorporations\nwas up by more than 11 per cent\nlast month.\nFrom the business community\ncame statements like these:\nThe chairman of the board of\nRepublic Steel, Charles M. White,\ndeclared that the liquidation of\nsteel inventories by manufactur\ners was just about over. When\nidle stocks are used, the mills,\nwhose scheduled operations fell\nlast week from 47 6 per cent of\ncapacity to 46.8 per cent, will\nbe calling laid-off workers back\nto fill new orders.\nThe president of General Elec- 1\ntrie Corp., Ralph J. Cordlner,.im\nported that his company, a large\nsteel user, had noted the \"flrst\nsigns\u201d of an upturn in demand 1\nfor electrical equipment and ap\npliances.\nDr John K. Langum. president\nof Business Economics, Inc., said\nthat allhough recovery will be\nslow it now is \u201csure and certain.\u201d\nHe predicted that the economy\nwill continue recessionary into\nthe fall, but the rate of decline\nhas started falling off.\nTempering somewhat these mod\nest expressions of hope were the\nlatest figures on unemployment\nclaims, which rose to a new post\nwar record the week ended April\n12 They were up 49.000 over the\nprevious week.\nThe other minus signs last week\nwere found mostly in those indices\nand business reports that mark\nthe course the economy already\nhas traveled. Fo; instance, pro\nduction of electric power in the\nweek ended April 19 dropped to\na nine-month low.\nThe Consumers' Price Index\nmeanwhile continued its unreces\nsionlike course. The latest survey\n\u2014for March\u2014found living costs\nat a new all-time high of 123.3 per\ncent of the 1947-9 average. A 1.8\nper cent rise in food costs, with\nfruits and vegetables up 51 per\ncent, led the rise.\nAuto Troubles\nIn the economically vital auto\nmobile industry, production levels\nlast week were expected to be at\nthe lowest point since the 1952\nsteel strike put the assembly lines\ninto low gear.\nChrysler reported a net loss of\n$15.1 million for the first quarter,\nwhen sales dropped 50 per cent\nfrom the year earlier. Ford's\nsales for the same period were\ndown almost as much as net in\ncome dropped from $1.85 a share\nin early 1957 to 42 cents this year.\nFollowing this news came the\nword that the Army had awarded\nChrysler contracts totaling $4.3\nmillion for trucks.\nOn the other hand. American\nMotors enjoying the success\nof their smgll Rambler model\n\u2014reported net profits in the six\nmonths ended March 31 climbed\nto $7.3 million, compared with\na net loss of $5.3 million in the\ncorresponding period a year ago.\nIn the steel industry. Bethle\nhem Steel, the industry\u2019s second\nlargest producer, reported its net\nincome down 54 per cent in the\nfirst quarter. Jones Si Laughlln's\nprofits in the same three months\nfell to 17 cents a share, from $1.89\nin the like 1957 period. And Na\ntional Steel's earnings dropped\nfrom $1.82 a share to 51 cents.\nThe Credit Contest\nOn Capitol Hill, meanwhile, a 1\nDemocratic backed plan for\nemergency unemployment bene-\nfits was stalled in the House Rules\nCommittee by an alliance of Re- 1\npublican and Southern Demo\ncrats. The Republicans generally 1\nprefer the administration\u2019s less\ncostly version of the bill, which\nwas bypassed by the Ways and\nMeans Committee; the Southern 1\nDemocrats are suspicious of both\nIflje Jhrnday fStaf\nWASHINGTON, D. C., APRIL 27, 1958\nTHE WEEK IN PERSPECTIVE\nfl 1 i \u2018JF\nKr hBUP I\nDETROIT AUTO WORKERS\u2014Is the tide of recession, which hos been hitting them so hord, obout to turn?\nplans. In which they see a possi\nble Federal encroachment on\nStates' rights.\nJockeying for the political credit\nthat is expected to go with re\ncession cures continued during\nthe week.\nVice President Nixon told a\npublishers\u2019 meeting that there\nwere indications that the moves\nalready taken by the Eisenhower\nadministration had licked the re\ncession. and that he did not ex\npect any new steps would be\nneeded. (He added, however, that\nif action already taken should\nturn out to be insufficient, he\nwould favor tax relief).\nSeveral days earlier. Senate\nDemocratic Leader Lyndon John\nson had said that the adminis\ntration had been too lethargic in\nits action ever since the recession\nbegan. The Nation, he said,\ncould not afford to \"sit it out.\u201d\nLabor Laws:\nRejected\nSenate Republican Leader Wil\nliam Knowland, like his mentor\nand predecessor. Robert Taft,\nhopes to be President. The late\n\u201cMr. Republican\u201d was thwarted\nin his ambition by the liberal wing\nof his party. Nevertheless, Sena\ntor Knowland is ready to gamble\nthat the Nation is more conserva\ntive than the \"modern Republi\ncans.\u201d\nHe hopes to reach the White\nHouse via the governorship of\nTHE WORLD SCENE\nThe Summit: Prospects Grow Dimmer\nPersonal, across-the-table di\nplomacy between heads of states\nis not new in history. But it has\nnot been the practice In modern\ntimes and. In terms of results, has\nlittle to recommend it.\nNapoleon met with Czar Alex\nander I for long hours alone, yet\nwithin months the Grand Army\nwas marching toward Moscow\u2014\nand disaster. Kaiser Wilhelm II\nand Czar Nicholas 11. \u201cWillie and\nNicky\u201d before 1914, yachted chum\nmily while they talked of the\nfuture of Europe. Both lost their\ncrowns in a war that saw their\nempires opposed in deadly strife.\nAdolf Hitler and Neville Cham\nberlain met to frame Munich\u2019s\nfalse \u201cpeace in our time.\"\nThere have been other meetings\nbetween heads-of-state, some of\nthem productive for a time.\nTeheran, Yalta and Potsdam,\nwhere the Soviet Union and the\nWestern allies met to co-ordinate\ntheir policies for war and for the\npeace to follow, were successful\nonly in respect to the war. The\nmost recent meeting, that in\nOeneva in 1955, raised the world's\nhopes for peace only to send them\ncrashing again as the cold war\ncontinued unabated.\nAn Appealing Idea\nBut whatever the history of\nsuch toprlevel talks, the idea has\npopular appeal, an appeal that\nseems to grow in proportion to\nthe gravity of the issues at stake.\nThe statesman who proposes a\nsummit meeting is almost auto\nmatically cast in the role of\npeacemaker. The statesman whe\nrejects or avoids a summit meet\ning, is likely to be called an\nobstructionist or worse.\nThus the Soviet Union\u2019s strong\nand sustained drive for a meet\ning of the heads-of-state has\nearned a great propaganda ad\nvantage for the KremUn. And, by\nthe same token. United States\nresistance to the idea tys created\na grave public relations problem\nfor the West.\nCalifornia, for which he has been\ncampaigning. A major issue in\nthe California race\u2014an issue he\ninjected\u2014is his proposed \"bill of\nrights\u201d for labor, a set of laws\nmore restrictive than those writ\nten by Benator Taft, which be\ncame known as the Taft-Hartley\nAct.\nFor this reason, the Benate\nstruggle over labor legislation last\nweek bad a definite bearing on\nnot only the California election\nthis fall, but possibly also on the\npresidential eleotion in 1960.\nIn that struggle Senator Know\nland did not fare well. Five times\nhis efforts to turn a bill requiring\nunions to report on welfare and\npension funds into a comprehen\nsive labor reform law by a series\nof amendments were rejected.\nOne Knowland amendment\nwoold have required unions to\nelect officers by secret ballot every\nfour years. Another would have\nset up controls for trusteeships\nover local unions. Others would\nhave made it illegal for an em\nployer representative to act at\nunion expense as a go-between\nin union-management negotia\ntions and would have allowed the\nSecretary of Labor to make pub\nlic financial information supplied\nby unions. One rejected late yes\nterday would have prohibited\nunions from discrimination in ac\ncepting members.\nSenator Knowland was opposed\nby ail Democrats except Senator\nLausche of Ohio and 10 Repub\nlicans. The position of many\nDemocrats and some Republicans\nwas that such legislation should\nLast week it was beginning to\nappear that the fencing between\nMoscow and Washington on the\nsubject of the summit was about\nover. The \u201cflsh-or-cut-bait\u201d stage\nseemed imminent. And the actual\nprospects for a heads-of-state\nmeeting were dimmer than they\nhave been at any time in the\npast year.\nDiplomats privately ascribe this\nsituation to two circumstances:\n(1) It is now plainly certain that\none side or the other must make\nsome major concessions in ad\nvance if a summit meeting is to\ntake place, and (2> there are\nspecific areas\u2014the West's insist\nence on strengthening NATO,\n*nd the Soviet refusal to discuss\nthe future of Eastern Europe\u2014\nwhere no agreement is possible\nat this time.\nDuring the week, the United\nStates, Britain and France again\nprodded the Soviet Union on in\nitiating joint talks in Moscow at\nthe ambassadorial level. So far,\nSoviet Foreign Minister Andrei\nOromyko has insisted on talking\nto the West\u2019s envoys separately\u2014\na procedure firmly rejected by the\nWest as divisive and fruitless. In\ncontrast to their earlier \"yes, but\nacceptance of a top-level\nconference, now the American.\nBritish and French notes were\nurging \u201cimmediate and practical\nsteps\" to bring one about.\nBasically, the United States and\nits allies are still insisting that the\nambassadorial talks, and a later\nforeign ministers meeting, con\nsider matters of substance as well\nas form. And the Russians con\ntinue to argue for preliminary\nsessions confined to procedural\nmatters, such as agenda, member\nship, and location.\nSAC at the U. N.\nSo far the Soviet leaders have\nelected to stand pat, and have\nadopted a \u201ctalk tough\u201d approach\nin contrast to soft-pedal\ndiplomacy of previous weeks The\nMoscow charge of April 17 that\nnot be \"written on the floor.\u201d\nSome Republicans also wanted to\nsee consideration of administra\ntion amendments offered by Sen\nator Smith of New Jersey, which\ndo not go so far as the Knowland\nproposals.\nPentagon Plan:\nEmbattled\nThe administration's blueprint\nfor reorganization es the Defense\nDepartment was in plenty of con\ngressionsd trouble last week, and\na retreat was already in progress\non some of its major provisions.\nDefense Secretary McElroy. at\nbay roost of the week before the\nsearching questioning of the\nHouse Armed Services Committee\nand its hostile Democratic chair\nman. Representative Carl Vinson\nof Georgia, agreed to a major\noverhaul of the administration a\nbill. Mr. McElroy\u2019s genial accept\nance of the committee's insistence\non rewriting the measure may\nhave headed off a fierce floor bat\ntle in both House and Senate.\nChief targets for the lawmakers'\nattack were provisions greatly\nstrengthening the Defense Secre\ntary's authority, and changes\nwhich might permit a de facto\nmerger of the three services. The\nlegislators were also highly suspi\ncious of clauses creating a cen\ntralized \"career\u201d general staff, and\nof others they feared would re\nmove or weaken the traditional\ncontrol of Congress over the\nAmerican bombers were endanger\ning the peace of the world by\nfrequent hydrogen bomb flights\nnear the Soviet borders was a\nsample of the stifler Russian\nattitude.\nThe formal complaint on the\nSAC flights was duly considered\nMonday by the U. N. Security\nCouncil. After Soviet Delegate\nArkady Sobolev stated the Moscow\ncharges. American Delegate Henry\nCabot Lodge replied with a flat\ndenial that the flights were a dan\nger to peace or represented ag\ngressive designs on Russia.\nMr. Sobolev withdrew the for\nmal complaint before the Security\nCouncil could vote. Mr. Lodge\nthen announced that the Russians\nhad suffered a \u201cdiplomatic de\nfeat\u201d by avoiding a vote certain\nto go against them.\nU. N. observers, however, could\ntee no embarrassment to the So\nviet Union in the withdrawal. De\nfeat in the Security Council, they\npointed out, was a foregone con\nclusion. (Britain, France, Nation\nalist China, the United States and\nthe Soviet Union are the perma\nnent members, with Canada, Co\nlombia. Iraq, Japan, Panama and\nSweden as temporary members\u2014\na piobable vote of 10 against one.)\nBut the Soviet objective of using\nthe U. N. as a sounding-board for\nthe bomber complaint was accom\nplished.\nSaturday, in an apparent after\nmath to the Soviet protest, Mr.\nLodge announced that the Se\ncurity Council on Tuesday would\ntake up, at the United States\u2019\nrequest, a discussion of Arctic\naerial inspection against surprise\nattack. (See story by William Frye\non Page A-27.)\nThe Big Gap\nOn the matter of weapons test\ning and production, the two great\npowers remained as far apart as\never last week.\nWhen the States rejected\nthe original Iroposal of Soviet\nPremier Khrusnchev that nuclear\ntesting be stopped. President\nTravel\nGeneral News\narmed services' basic roles and\nmissions.,\nPresident Eisenhower's annoy*\nance at critics of his bill was clear\nagain Wednesday, when ha\nsnapped angrily at a reporter who\nasked whether the administration\nbill might permit a \"personalized\nmilitary force\" Flushing and\nbrusque. Mr. Elsenhower rasped\n\u201cit might be Just as well, sensible\nfor you to say that the Congress\nla suddenly going nuts and com\npletely abolishing the Defense De\npartment.\u201d\nPay Raises:\nDue for Veto?\nIn recent weeks. President\nEisenhower\u2019s relations with Con\ngress\u2014for so long remarkably\nsmooth\u2014have reached the lowest\nebb since he entered the White\nHouse. Vetoes and the threat of\nvetoes have become more numer\nous as an election-minded Con\ngress seems less inclined to see\neye-to-eye with the President.\nLast week. Senate-House con\nferees approved postal rate and\npay increases that\u2014if their ver\nsion survives floor tests\u2014may well\nrun into another presidential veto.\nThe conference committee ap\nproved a flat 4-cent first-class\nmall rate and an across-the-board\npostal pay increase, retroactive\nto last January 1, of 7 J per cent\nplus temporary cost -of living\nbonuses of 1.5 to 2.5 per cent.\nMr. Eisenhower, who has asked\nfor a 5-cent letter rate, has made\nit plain that he would not accept\nany pay Increase plan that went\nfar beyond a 6 per cent rise.\nMeanwhile, the Senate Armed\nServices Committee unanimously\napproved a bill to raise the pay of\ncareer military men by about $577\nmillion in the fiscal year beginning\nJuly 1.\nSupreme Court:\nWing Clipper\nLast year. Republican Senator\nJenner of Indiana introduced a\nbill to restrict the Supreme\nCourt's authority to declare un\nconstitutional anti Communist\nmeasures taken by the Federal\nand State governments.\nThe bill was clearly an angry\nrejoinder to the series of recent\ndecisions which have upheld the\nrights of people accused of sub\nversive activity.\nBut its drastic terms drew the\nformidable opposition of the\nAmerican Bar Association, many\nlaw school deans, historians, and\nthe Attorney General. Thereupon\na revision of the Jenner bill, in\nthe form of an amendment, was\nintroduced by Senator Butler,\nMaryland Republican, to accom\nplish the same purposes.\nLast week the Senate Judiciary\nCommittee reported favorably on\ntwo of the five sections of the\nButler amendment.\nOne of the approved sections\nwould prohibit the Supreme\nCourt from acoepting jurisdiction\nin any case involving State laws\nfor membership to the bar. The\nother would permit Congressional\ncommittees to be the sole judge;\nof whether questions they ask of\nwitnesses are pertinent to the\naims of the inquiry in progress.\nEisenhower countered with tha\nsuggestion that \"technicians\" from\nboth sides begin a study of \"what\nspecific control measures are nec\nessary if there is to be a depend\nable and agreed disarmament\nprogram.\u201d He also declared that\nany test ban must be linked to\nthe cessation of manufacture of\nfissionable materials for military\npurposes.\nOn Wednesday. Mr. Khru\nshchev rejected the Eisenhower\nproposal. In a 15-page letter ha\ndeclared that a study by tech\nnicians would be of |ittle avail if\nthe responsible authorities had\nnot first arrived at some under\nstanding.\nIn the matter of an agreement\nto limit space exploration and\ntravel to peaceful purposes, Mr.\nKhrushchev repeated the previous\nSoviet position: To ban outer\nspace military operations today\nwould, in effect, prevent the So\nviet Union from further progress\non its Intercontinental ballistics\nmissile. But American bases for\nnuclear bombers in foreign na\ntions would not be affected. There\nfore, said the Russian Premier,\nany ban on military use of outer\nspace must be accompanied by a\nsimilar ban on American bases\ncapable of launching conventional\nbombers against Soviet territory.\nOn Tuesday, Secretary Dulles\nsaid that the United States would\nnot negotiate with the Soviet Un\nion \u201cunder the rules the chal\nlenger lays down.\"\nNo 'Tete a Tete'\nPresident Eisenhower, in a press\nconference Wednesday marked by\nseveral flashes of the Eisenhower\ntemper, ruled out any two-power\nmeeting with Mr. Khrushchev.\nCommitments of the United States\nto its allies, the President ob\nserved, would make a meeting\nbetween himself and Mr. Khru\nshchev \u2018\u2018difficult to justify.\u201d\nWhat seemed increasingly clear\nlast week in the dickering between\nWashington find Moscow fas that\nneither side was willing to make\nContinued on Page A-2F\nA-25","height":"29512","width":"18306"}}
